title: Grateful Dead Live at Greensboro Coliseum on 1980-05-01
lineage: FOB (Nakamichi 700)> Master Cassette (Sony TC-D5); A>D: Master Cassette (Tascam 112mkIII)>Sony R500 @44.1>; D>CD: DAT> MASTER CDR on HHB CDR 850> Duped to CD(1) on Tascam CD-D4000MKII; CD>SHN: EAC (see info)> Soundforge> CD WAV> SHNv3
description: Alabama Getaway-> Promised Land, Candyman, Me & My Uncle-> Big River, Althea, Easy To Love You, Minglewood Blues, Sugaree, Lost Sailor-> Saint Of Circumstance-> Deal Feel Like A Stranger, Don't Ease Me In, Estimated Prophet-> Uncle John's Band-> Drums-> Wharf Rat-> Around & Around-> Johnny B. Goode, E: Brokedown Palace

reviews.review_text: Right On!! This show was right on!! The quality could be better, but 5 stars for my 1st show.

venue? during minglewood bobby sings, "in nyc, where the little girls know what to do. . ?"  correct venue?  

otherwise, great audience show!  cranking it now.

only time? i'm pretty sure there is not another transition like this estimated/uncle johns. i had to listen to it several times to make sure it was'nt a splice. completely out of the blue moment. the rat is really nice and the around/j.b. goode transition is another oddity. j.b. goode is one of the best jerry versions. whole show is worth a listen. jerry has major vocal flub in promised that's more funny than painful. 5 stars for unique moments. don't give up at the beginning, the sound clears quite a bit. if you can tolerate a little trivia... in the dead family album they list the gross ticket sale amounts for each venue on this tour and after doing the math it looks like there were only @ 6,000 people at this show. (it held @15,000 in 1980) they were playing hard for a 1/2 empty building. the shows up north on that tour mainly sold out and brought it tons more money than the southern shows. it must have been strange for the dead to see the explosion of fans after having flown under the radar for so long. double edged sword. like being forced to get a real job, making more money but having to tuck in your shirt and shave. this sugaree is starting to catch fire  and the sound is not bad for an audience.
this is an awesome venue and this AUD is pretty damn sweet!! definitely check out the estimated > uncle john's transition. the entire second set fits on one disc.

It was an awesome venue, and the Dead never played a bad show there.I didn't see this but I saw the '89 and '91 shows there.It had an intimate feel and wasn't all that big.This is a great show and sound is good.
great recording the estimated in mind blowing jerry is on the whole night and nice licks in minglewood
WHOPPER No downers in this show. Do your ears a favor and stream this show

Great Show On The Heels Of Some Duds This is a great show after the otherwise poor showings in Atlanta and Birmingham.  Sound here is pretty good and gives you that "there" feeling.  High points are definitely the Uncle John > Jam, and  everything post-Space is JUMPIN'.  I guess a low point (if any) would be a somewhat standard opening to the 1st set until they reach Big River, which accelerates the show to the level it would remain at until the end.

Get this one.

Historical significance A great show, with polysemic depth.  All you statisticians from Canarsie (or a look at Deadbase) can  correct me on this one, but I believe this night was the breakout, after a long hiatus, of Uncle John's and Brokedown (I heard them sound check Brokedown while I was lurking around the venue).  This was significant because this was the Dead's first time in Greensboro after the Klan Massacre  ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greensboro_massacre ), and I like to think they were making a statement.
